are of PS2s, and i think i know your problem,and could fix it if i could see your system, unfortunately i cannot, But the problem seems simple enough to explain.<br>
<br>
The scratch at 1&quot; from the center means that there's a raised piece of plastic on the tray that holds the CD, this means that you won't have to take it apart to fix it.  Unfortunately, it will be very difficult to fix without making it worse.<br>
<br>
The operation is simple.  Open the tray, then softly move your finger around the spot that's about 1&quot; from the center.  You should feel a little scrape when you get to the problem spot.  if you don't, it's too small to feel and you need better equipment, or it's another problem altogether (which is unlikely).<br>
<br>
If you do find it, you can either sand it off softly, with an incredibly high grit sand paper, or put a small piece of electric tape over it.  The electric tape solution may cause your PS2's loading speed to slow a little, but the scratches will stop.<br>
<br>
If that doesn't solve it, then it's probably the laser.  Not the laser itself, but the plastic casing that doesn't move.  If this is the case, you have to take it apart, so you'll need a set of Jeweller's screwdrivers and a lot of patience.  Also a good memory, because you have to completely disasemble it to get to the laser.<br>
<br>
I hope this helped.  good luck. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table><br><font color=#336699>- </font><a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs>Polykarbon BBS</a><font color=#336699> - </font><a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm31>Help, Hints and Cheats</a> <font color=#336699> - </font><a href="http://www.polykarbon.com">Polykarbon: Manga & Photoshop</a><font color=#336699> - </font><br><br><br><br>Powered By <a href=http://www.ezboard.com/>ezboard®</a> Ver. 7.246j<br>Copyright ©1999-2003 ezboard, Inc.</center></body></html>  

